## Final response
Improper use of the Java API can lead to vulnerabilities in web applications. Here's an example of a vulnerable code snippet that demonstrates a common mistake:

```java
// Vulnerable code snippet: Using a deprecated method to parse JSON data
import com.google.gson.Gson;
import com.google.gson.JsonElement;
import com.google.gson.JsonObject;

public class VulnerableParser {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String json = "{\"name\":\"John\",\"age\":30}";
        JsonElement element = new Gson().fromJson(json, JsonElement.class);
        JsonObject jsonObject = element.getAsJsonObject();
        System.out.println(jsonObject.get("name")); // vulnerable to JSON injection attacks
    }
}
```

***

```java
// Safe code snippet: Using a secure method to parse JSON data
import com.google.gson.Gson;
import com.google.gson.JsonElement;
import com.google.gson.JsonObject;

public class SafeParser {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String json = "{\"name\":\"John\",\"age\":30}";
        Gson gson = new Gson();
        JsonObject jsonObject = gson.fromJson(json, JsonObject.class);
        System.out.println(jsonObject.get("name")); // safe and secure
    }
}
```

In the vulnerable code snippet, the `fromJson` method is used to parse the JSON data, which can lead to JSON injection attacks if the input data is not properly sanitized. In the safe code snippet, the `fromJson` method is used with the correct type parameter (`JsonObject.class`) to prevent this vulnerability.

